<body>

<h1>An Act to amend the Criminal Code (independence of the judiciary)</h1>

<h2>Bill Number: <strong>S-213</strong></h2>
<h2>Current Status: <strong>At consideration in committee in the Senate</strong></h2>
<h2>Last Major Stage Completed: <strong>Second reading in the Senate</strong></h2>
<h2>Parliament Session: <strong>44th Parliament, 1st session</strong></h2>

<h3>Senate Readings:</h3>
<ul>
    <li>First - <strong>Completed</strong></li>
    <li>Second - <strong>Completed</strong></li>
    <li>Third - <strong>Not Completed</strong></li>
</ul>

<h3>House Readings:</h3>
<ul>
    <li>First - <strong>Not Completed</strong></li>
    <li>Second - <strong>Not Completed</strong></li>
    <li>Third - <strong>Not Completed</strong></li>
</ul>

<h2>Royal Assent: <strong>Not Completed</strong></h2>

<h2>Sponsor: <strong>Sen. Hon. Mobina S.B. Jaffer</strong></h2>
<h2>Bill Type: <strong>Senate Public Bill</strong></h2>

<h3>Summary</h3>
<p>This enactment amends the Criminal Code to give a court the discretion to vary the punishment to be imposed in respect of an offence for which the punishment — or different degrees or kinds of punishment — is prescribed in an enactment.</p>
<p>It allows a court to decide to not make a mandatory prohibition order provided for under a provision of that Act — or to add conditions or vary any of the conditions set out in that provision.</p>

<h3>Contact Information</h3>
<p>If you have any questions or comments regarding the accessibility of this publication, please contact us at <a href="mailto:accessible@parl.gc.ca">accessible@parl.gc.ca</a>.</p>

</body>
</html>
